tes, Frankrijk","Burstwick, Yorkshire, England":"Burstwick, Yorkshire, England","England":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1155–1194":"1155–1194","–Female":"Deceased","–1214":"–1214","1195–1249":"1195–1249","–Male":"Deceased","1249":"1249","1214":"1214","after 3 July 1190":"after 3 July 1190","1155":"1155","1175":"1175","1195":"1195","1194":"1194","Fors, Deux-Sevres, Poitou-Charentes, France":"Fors, Deux-Sèvres, Poitou-Charentes, France","Burstwick, Yorkshire, England":"Burstwick, Yorkshire, England","England":"England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Forz","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: topographic name for someone who lived near a ford (Middle English, Old English <i>ford</i>), or a habitational name from one of the many places called with this word, such as Ford (Durham, Herefordshire, Northumberland, Shropshire, Sussex), Ford in Sefton (Lancashire), Ford in Crediton and Ford in Holcombe Rogus (both Devon), Ford in Litton and Ford in Wiveliscombe (both Somerset).","Irish: Anglicized form (quasi-translation) of various Gaelic names, for example <b>MacGiolla na Naomh</b> ‘son of <i>Gilla na Naomh</i>’ (a personal name meaning ‘servant of the saints’), <b>Mac Conshámha</b> ‘son of <i>Conshnámha</i>’ (a personal name composed of the elements <i>con</i> ‘dog’ + <i>snámh</i> ‘to swim’), in all of which the final syllable was wrongly thought to be <i>áth</i> ‘ford’, and <b>Ó Fuar(th)áin</b> (see   Foran  ).","Americanized form of French   Faure   ‘blacksmith’."],"variants":[{"name":"Forth","meanings":["English: variant of   Ford   1.","German: topographic name for someone who lived by a ford, Middle High German <i>vort</i>, <i>vurt</i>, Middle Low German <i>vorde</i> ‘ford, entrance way’, or a habitational name from a place in Franconia or in former Pomerania (now Poland) named Forth."]},{"name":"Foard","meanings":["English: variant of   Ford  ."]},{"name":"Forde","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Declan, Dermot, Aine, Fionnuala, Liam, Nuala.","English and Irish: variant of   Ford   1 and 2. This is a very common spelling in Ireland.","Norwegian (<b>Førde</b>): habitational name from any of numerous farmsteads named Førde (there are eleven on the west coast), from Old Norse <i>fyrthi</i>, dative of <i>fjǫrthr</i> ‘fjord’."]},{"name":"Foran","meanings":["Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Fuartháin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Fuarthán</i>’, a personal name derived from <i>fuar</i> ‘cold’. The word <i>fuarán</i> also means ‘spring’ or ‘pool’. The form <i>Fuarthán</i> was understood as <i>fuarathán</i> ‘cold little ford’, and the name has thus sometimes been translated into English as   Ford  ."]}]},{"name":"Guillaume","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Germanic.  See  <b>William</b> ."],"variants":[{"name":"William","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Comte Guillaume de Forz I d'Aumale was born in 1155, in Fors, Deux-Sèvres, Poitou-Charentes, France as the son of Boson d’Vivonne. He married Henriette d'Aumâle after 3 July 1190. He died in 1194, in Burstwick, Yorkshire, England, at the age of 39."},"et":{"1155–1194":"1155–1194","–Female":"Surnud","–1214":"–1214","1195–1249":"1195–1249","–Male":"Surnud","1249":"1249","1214":"1214","after 3 July 1190":"pärast 3. juulit 1190","1155":"1155","1175":"1175","1195":"1195","1194":"1194","Fors, Deux-Sevres, Poitou-Charentes, France":"Fors, Deux-Sèvres, Poitou-Charentes, Prantsusmaa","Burstwick, Yorkshire, England":"Burstwick, Yorkshire, England","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1155–1194":"1155–1194","–Female":"Kuollut","–1214":"–1214","1195–1249":"1195–1249","–Male":"Kuollut","1249":"1249","1214":"1214","after 3 July 1190":"3. heinäkuuta 1190 jälkeen","1155":"1155","1175":"1175","1195":"1195","1194":"1194","Fors, Deux-Sevres, Poitou-Charentes, France":"Fors, Deux-Sèvres, Poitou-Charentes, Ranska","Burstwick, Yorkshire, England":"Burstwick, Yorkshire, England","England":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1155–1194":"1155–1194","–Female":"Décédée","–1214":"–1214","1195–1249":"1195–1249","–Male":"Décédé","1249":"1249","1214":"1214","after 3 July 1190":"après 3 juillet 1190","1155":"1155","1175":"1175","1195":"1195","1194":"1194","Fors, Deux-Sevres, Poitou-Charentes, France":"Fors, Deux-Sèvres, Poitou-Charentes, France","Burstwick, Yorkshire, England":"Burstwick, Everwyck, Angleterre","England":"Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Comte Guillaume de Forz I d'Aumale est né en 1155, à Fors, Deux-Sèvres, Poitou-Charentes, France, fils de Boson d’